#  Helm Basics – Nginx Deployment in Kubernetes

##  Overview

This project demonstrates the **basic usage of Helm in Kubernetes**, including:

* Installing Helm
* Adding a Helm repository
* Searching for charts
* Rendering Kubernetes manifests
* Deploying an application using Helm

---

##  Prerequisites

* Kubernetes cluster (EKS / Minikube / Kubeadm)
* `kubectl` configured
* Internet access

---

## 🔧 Step 1: Install Helm

```bash
curl -fsSL -o get_helm.sh https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-4
chmod 700 get_helm.sh
./get_helm.sh
```

Verify installation:

```bash
helm version
```

---

##  Step 2: Add Helm Repository

Add Bitnami repository:

```bash
helm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami
```

Update repo:

```bash
helm repo update
```

---

##  Step 3: Search Helm Charts

```bash
helm search repo
```

Search for specific chart:

```bash
helm search repo nginx
```

---

##  Step 4: Render YAML (Dry Run)

Before installing, you can preview the Kubernetes manifests:

```bash
helm template myapp bitnami/nginx
```

This helps to:

* Understand generated resources
* Debug configurations
* Customize values before deployment

---

##  Step 5: Install Nginx using Helm

```bash
helm install myapp bitnami/nginx
```

---

##  Step 6: Verify Deployment

Check Helm release:

```bash
helm list
```

Check Kubernetes resources:

```bash
kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc
```

---

## Step 7: Access Application

If service type is `LoadBalancer`, get external URL:

```bash
kubectl get svc
```

Then access in browser:

```
http://<EXTERNAL-IP>
```




